Why I choose candidate 2
- Candidate 2 matches almost verbatim the core late‑’80s production attributes I favor: punchy, syncopated drum‑machine grooves and warm analog synth textures create the rhythmic and tonal foundation I prefer. 
- It explicitly notes meticulous engineering that "preserves dynamic headroom" and "ambiently framed, lyric‑forward vocals" — both are key priorities: I want vocals present and intelligible without aggressive close‑mic harshness, and I want headroom and transient detail preserved rather than squashed. 
- The presence of layered harmonies, tasteful guitar/piano accents and concise single‑disc sequencing directly aligns with my taste for clear arrangements that support vocals and groove without sprawling or over‑orchestrating. 
- Because candidate 2 emphasizes roomy midrange, meticulous engineering and the specific drum/synth palette, it will likely reveal instrumental detail and rhythmic clarity—exactly what I look for in a remaster/mix.
Why I reject candidate 1
- While candidate 1 hits some of my AOR sympathies (multi‑tracked guitars, stacked harmonies, analog‑rooted production and preserved transients), it also presents clear conflicts with my dislikes and primary preferences.
- The description calls out a "gravelly dry lead up front" — a front‑of‑mix, dry vocal presentation that I explicitly dislike because it tends to be close‑mic harsh and robs the ambient framing I prefer. That is a deal‑breaker relative to my priority for ambiently framed, lyric‑forward vocals.
- The record is described as midrange‑forward, riff‑driven arena rock with aggressive crunchy guitars and tight gated drums. Those qualities move away from the late‑’80s punchy, synthesized groove aesthetic I currently favor; gated drums and aggressive guitar up front can compete with vocals and reduce the kind of rhythmic subtlety and headroom I prize.
- Although it preserves transients and dynamics (a plus), the combination of up‑front gravelly vocals and arena‑style aggressive guitar focus means it would not deliver the ambient vocal framing, synth texture, and meticulous preservation of headroom/ instrumental detail that make candidate 2 a better match.
Summary
Candidate 2 aligns far more closely with the stated production, vocal treatment and rhythmic/synth textures I prefer, while candidate 1, despite some AOR elements I like, conflicts with my dislike of front‑of‑mix dry vocals and the arena guitar/drum emphasis. For those reasons I select candidate 2.

