cy: forward‑intimate center vocals, restrained guitars, minimal overdubs, and concise singles sequencing. While it does offer warm analogue character and preserves headroom with light compression, it is a singles anthology (i.e., hit‑stacked), and it favors front‑of‑mix vocal intimacy and restrained guitar work rather than the large, layered, guitar‑centric AOR sound I prize.\nWhy I chose Candidate 2 and rejected Candidate 1:\n- Candidate 2 aligns with the most important and specific parts of my preference set. I prioritize layered, multi‑tracked electric guitars, roomy analog reverb and sheen, wide stereo imaging, punchy low end and tight rhythmic snap, plus full‑length expressive solos and album‑like sequencing. The 1976 AOR mix explicitly promises those attributes. Its restrained remaster that preserves headroom and wide dynamics is exactly the opposite of the brick‑wall compression and flattened dynamics I dislike.\n- Candidate 1 conflicts with several explicit dislikes and lower‑priority preferences. It is a concise singles anthology — effectively a hit compilation — and my self‑introduction specifically calls out a dislike of hit‑stacked compilations that destroy album flow and sequencing. Its forward‑intimate center vocals and restrained guitars also run counter to my preference for ambient, blended lead vocals that sit in the band and for mid‑forward, multi‑tracked guitar sheen. Although Candidate 1 preserves headroom and offers warmth, its production aesthetic (vocal‑forward immediacy and minimal overdubs) is not what I seek for classic late‑’70s AOR studio textures.\n- In short, Candidate 2 delivers the roomy, guitar‑driven, tape‑warm AOR studio sound, dynamic preservation, and multi‑layered instrumental depth that match my priorities. Candidate 1, while well remastered for vocal immediacy, sacrifices the layered guitar focus, album continuity and ambient vocal/ensemble placement that define what I’m looking for.'. \n\n However, upon actually listening to 